{{Use dmy dates|date=March 2014}} {{Use British English|date=March 2014}} {{Infobox football biography | name = Billy Garton | image = | fullname = William Francis Garton | birth_date = {{birth date and age|1965|3|15|df=y}} | birth_place = [[City of Salford|Salford]], England | height = {{convert|180|cm|ftin|abbr=on}} | position = [[Defender (association football)#Centre-back|Centre-back]] | youthyears1 = |youthclubs1 = | years1 = 1984–1990 |clubs1 = [[Manchester United F.C.|Manchester United]] |caps1 = 41 |goals1 = 0 | years2 = 1986 |clubs2 = → [[Birmingham City F.C.|Birmingham City]] (loan) |caps2 = 5 |goals2 = 0 | years3 = 1992–1993 |clubs3 = [[Salford City F.C.|Salford City]] |caps3 = |goals3 = | years4 = 1993–1994 |clubs4 = [[Witton Albion F.C.|Witton Albion]] |caps4 = |goals4 = | years5 = 1994–1998 |clubs5 = [[Hyde United F.C.|Hyde United]] |caps5 = 100 |goals5 = 1 | years6 = 2000–2001 |clubs6 = [[Salford City F.C.|Salford City]] |caps6 = |goals6 = | totalcaps = |totalgoals = | manageryears1 = 1992–1993 | managerclubs1 = [[Salford City F.C.|Salford City]] }} '''William Francis Garton''' (born 15 March 1965) is a former [[association football|footballer]] who played in [[the Football League]] for [[Manchester United F.C.|Manchester United]] and [[Birmingham City F.C.|Birmingham City]].<ref name=news>{{cite news |url=https://www.manchestereveningnews.co.uk/sport/football/football-news/gartons-tale-helps-revive-forgotten-1047724 |title=Garton's tale helps revive forgotten era |first=Stuart |last=Brennan |newspaper=Manchester Evening News |date=9 November 2006 |accessdate=18 February 2018}}</ref> He made his United debut in 1984 and played 51 games, the first half of his career marred by an injury, and was forced to retire from full-time football after being diagnosed with [[chronic fatigue syndrome]].<ref name = news/> He later played for local clubs<ref name = news/><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.hydeunited.com/playerstats.php?p=205 |title=Player details: Billy Garton |website=Hyde United Football Club Database |publisher=Stephen Shaw |accessdate=18 February 2018}}</ref> and taught, emigrating to [[San Diego]], [[California]] in 2001<ref name = news/> and co-founded the Carmel Valley Manchester youth soccer club.<ref>{{cite web |title=Directors |accessdate=28 April 2012 |url=http://manchestersoccer.net/?page_id=284 }}</ref>
