{{for|the ABC Local Radio presenter|Elizabeth Jackson (journalist)}}
{{Use dmy dates|date=July 2011}}
{{Use Australian English|date=July 2011}}
'''Liz Jackson'''  (1951 – 27 June 2018) was an [[Australia]]n [[journalist]] and [[barrister]] noted for her work on the ''[[Four Corners (Australian TV program)|Four Corners]]'' and  ''[[Media Watch (TV program)|Media Watch]]'' television programs. She received nine [[Walkley Award]]s for excellence in journalism.

==Career ==
Jackson grew up in [[Melbourne]], Australia and commenced work with the [[Australian Broadcasting Corporation]] (ABC) in 1986. Prior to her career with the ABC, Jackson also worked in a community legal centre in Australia and practised law in [[London]] as a barrister at [[Gray's Inn]]. Jackson returned to Australia and worked for the NSW Premier's Department, in the Women's Coordination Unit, dealing with laws to protect women from violence.<ref>[http://www.abc.net.au/news/2016-11-17/liz-jackson-biography/8031224 Liz Jackson: One of Australia's finest journalists]; abc.net.au</ref>

After joining ''Four Corners'' as an investigative reporter in 1994, Jackson was awarded [[Walkley Award]]s, Australia's awards for journalism, on five occasions for her work on the following:
*The situation in [[Somalia]] (1993);
*The suicide of Aboriginal activist [[Rob Riley (Aboriginal activist)|Rob Riley]];
*"Fixing Cricket", a report about cricket match-fixing (2000);
*"Go to jail", regarding the [[Northern Territory]]'s mandatory sentencing laws (2000); and,
*"Putting the Children at Risk", an investigation into the [[New South Wales]] Government Department of Community Services (2002).<ref name="abc.net.au">[http://www.abc.net.au/4corners/reporter_lizjackson.htm Biography of Liz Jackson], ''Four Corners'' website, [[Australian Broadcasting Corporation]], accessed 11 July 2007.</ref>

Jackson received three [[Logie Award]]s for "Fixing Cricket" and stories related to the [[Australian Special Air Service Regiment#Blackhawk accident|Blackhawk disaster]] and [[HIV]] transmission from a [[doctor's office|doctor's surgery]].<ref name="abc.net.au"/>

At the start of 2005, Jackson hosted the media-criticism program ''Media Watch'', before stepping down in December 2005 and returning to ''Four Corners''.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.smh.com.au/news/national/attard-fronts-media-watch/2005/12/07/1133829602483.html|title=Attard fronts Media Watch|date=7 December 2005|publisher=[[Sydney Morning Herald]]|accessdate=2007-05-02}}</ref>

==Personal life ==
Her daughter, [[Rose Jackson (politician)|Rose Jackson]], is a student politician aligned with the [[National Labor Students]] faction and sits on the executive of the [[Australian Labor Party|New South Wales Labor Party]].

In November 2016, Jackson revealed she had been diagnosed with [[Parkinson's disease]] in 2014, with the release of a documentary called "A Sense of Self" broadcast as an episode of ''Four Corners''.<ref>[http://www.abc.net.au/news/2016-11-17/liz-jackson-living-with-parkinson's-disease/8029626 A Sense Of Self], ''Four Corners'', 21 November 2016.</ref>

She died in her sleep while on holiday in Greece on 27 June 2018, at the age of 67.<ref>ABC News, '[http://www.abc.net.au/news/2018-06-28/liz-jackson-former-abc-journalist-dies/9921518 Liz Jackson, former ABC journalist, dies aged 67'], 28 June 2018.</ref>

