'''Miroslav Kusý''' (born 1 December 1931 in [[Bratislava]]) is a [[Slovaks|Slovak]] political scientist and politician. Described as a "dissident" of [[Czechoslovakia]]'s communist regime,<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1989/12/10/nyregion/upheaval-east-hard-line-czech-president-quit-dissident-seen-successor.html?pagewanted=all|title=UPHEAVAL IN THE EAST; Hard-Line Czech President to Quit And Dissident Is Seen as Successor|last=Tagliabue|first=John|date=10 December 1989|publisher=[[New York Times]]|accessdate=22 January 2010}}</ref> he was given an eight-month suspended sentence in November 1989 for an anti-government protest.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://news.google.com/newspapers?id=EkwcAAAAIBAJ&sjid=234EAAAAIBAJ&pg=6994,403542&dq=miroslav-kusy&hl=en|title=Czechoslovakia remains out of step|date=16 November 1989|publisher=The Milkwaukee Journal|accessdate=22 January 2010}}</ref> After the [[Velvet Revolution]], Kusý was appointed as chairman of the Federal Press and Information Office of [[Czechoslovakia]].<ref>{{cite book|last=Elster|first=Jon|title=The roundtable talks and the breakdown of communism|publisher=University of Chicago Press|year=1996|pages=158|isbn=0-226-20628-9|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=KQZIjbQri0gC&dq=%22Miroslav+Kusy%22+Minister&source=gbs_navlinks_s|accessdate=23 January 2010}}</ref>
After politics, Kusý became a professor in political science.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.bloomberg.com/apps/news?pid=newsarchive&sid=a4cIoEzjbRpY&refer=europe-redirectoldpage|title=Slovak Lawmakers Approve Early Elections for June 17 (Update1) |date=9 February 2009|publisher=Bloomberg|accessdate=22 January 2010}}</ref>
