{{BLP sources|date=February 2013}} {{Infobox scientist | name = Stephen Harrison |birth_name = Stephen C. Harrison | image = Professor Stephen Harrison ForMemRS.jpg | imagesize = | alt = | caption = Stephen Harrison in 2014, portrait via the [[Royal Society]] | birth_date = <!--{{birth date |YYYY|MM|DD}}--> | birth_place = | death_date = <!--{{death date and age |YYYY|MM|DD |YYYY|MM|DD}} (death date then birth date)--> | death_place = | death_cause = | resting_place = | resting_place_coordinates = <!--{{coord|LAT|LONG|type:landmark|display=inline,title}}--> | other_names = | residence = | citizenship = | nationality = | fields = | workplaces = | patrons = | alma_mater = [[Harvard University]] (BA, PhD) | thesis_title = <!--(or | thesis1_title = and | thesis2_title = )--> | thesis_url = <!--(or | thesis1_url = and | thesis2_url = )--> | thesis_year = <!--(or | thesis1_year = and | thesis2_year = )--> | doctoral_advisor = | academic_advisors = | doctoral_students = | notable_students = | known_for = | influences = | influenced = | awards = | spouse = <!--(or | spouses = )--> | partner = <!--(or | partners = )--> | children = | signature = <!--(filename only)--> | signature_alt = | website = {{URL|https://crystal.harvard.edu/harrison.html}} | footnotes = }}
'''Stephen C. Harrison''' is professor of biological chemistry and molecular pharmacology, professor of pediatrics, and director of the Center for Molecular and Cellular Dynamics of [[Harvard Medical School]], head of the Laboratory of Molecular Medicine at [[Boston Children's Hospital]], and investigator of the [[Howard Hughes Medical Institute]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.newsrx.com/newsletters/AIDS-Vaccine-Week/2005-08-22/082220053336AV.html |title=Awards - Stephen C. Harrison wins Bristol-Myers Squibb infectious diseases r |publisher=Newsrx.com |date=2005-08-22 |accessdate=2013-01-29}}</ref>
==Education and career== He received his B.A. in chemistry and physics from Harvard in 1963, and was then a Henry fellow at the [[MRC Laboratory of Molecular Biology]] at [[Cambridge]]. In 1967, he received his Ph.D. in biophysics from Harvard, was a research fellow there as well as a junior fellow in the Society of Fellows, and joined the Harvard faculty in 1971.
==Research== His wide-ranging studies of protein structure have contributed insights to [[virus|viral]] architecture, [[DNA]]–[[protein]] recognition, and [[cellular signaling]].
Harrison has made important contributions to [[structural biology]], most notably by determining and analyzing the structures of viruses and viral proteins, by [[crystallographic]] analysis of protein–DNA complexes,<ref>{{cite journal |vauthors=Anderson JE, Ptashne M, Harrison SC |title=Structure of the repressor-operator complex of bacteriophage 434 |journal=Nature |volume=326 |issue=6116 |pages=846–52 |year=1987 |pmid=3553959 |doi=10.1038/326846a0 |url=}}</ref><ref>{{cite journal |vauthors=Ellenberger TE, Brandl CJ, Struhl K, Harrison SC |title=The GCN4 basic region leucine zipper binds DNA as a dimer of uninterrupted alpha helices: crystal structure of the protein-DNA complex |journal=Cell |volume=71 |issue=7 |pages=1223–37 |date=December 1992 |pmid=1473154 |doi= 10.1016/s0092-8674(05)80070-4|url=}}</ref> and by structural studies of [[protein kinase|protein-kinase]] switching mechanisms.<ref>{{cite journal |vauthors=Xu W, Harrison SC, Eck MJ |title=Three-dimensional structure of the tyrosine kinase c-Src |journal=Nature |volume=385 |issue=6617 |pages=595–602 |date=February 1997 |pmid=9024657 |doi=10.1038/385595a0 |url=}}</ref> The initiator of high-resolution virus crystallography, he has moved from his early work on [[tomato bushy stunt virus]] <ref>{{cite journal |author=Harrison SC |title=Structure of tomato bushy stunt virus. I. The spherically averaged electron density |journal=J. Mol. Biol. |volume=42 |issue=3 |pages=457–83 |date=June 1969 |pmid=5804155 |doi=10.1016/0022-2836(69)90236-8 }}</ref> (1978) to the study of more complex human pathogens, including the [[capsid]] of [[human papillomavirus]],<ref>{{cite journal |vauthors=Modis Y, Trus BL, Harrison SC |title=Atomic model of the papillomavirus capsid |journal=EMBO J. |volume=21 |issue=18 |pages=4754–62 |date=September 2002 |pmid=12234916 |pmc=126290 |doi= 10.1093/emboj/cdf494|url=}}</ref> the envelope of [[dengue virus]],<ref>{{cite journal |vauthors=Modis Y, Ogata S, Clements D, Harrison SC |title=Structure of the dengue virus envelope protein after membrane fusion |journal=Nature |volume=427 |issue=6972 |pages=313–9 |date=January 2004 |pmid=14737159 |doi=10.1038/nature02165 |url=}}</ref> and several components of [[HIV]].<ref>{{cite journal |vauthors=Huang H, Chopra R, Verdine GL, Harrison SC |title=Structure of a covalently trapped catalytic complex of HIV-1 reverse transcriptase: implications for drug resistance |journal=Science |volume=282 |issue=5394 |pages=1669–75 |date=November 1998 |pmid=9831551 |doi= 10.1126/science.282.5394.1669|url=}}</ref> He has also turned some of his research attention to even more complex assemblies, such as [[clathrin-coated vesicle]]s.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://chavi.org/about-chavi/investigators/stephen-c-harrison-phd |title=Archived copy |accessdate=2013-01-12 |deadurl=yes |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140514054328/http://chavi.org/about-chavi/investigators/stephen-c-harrison-phd |archivedate=2014-05-14 |df= }}</ref> He led the Structural Biology team at the Center for HIV/AIDS Vaccine Immunology (CHAVI) when it received [[National Institute of Allergy and Infectious Diseases]] (NIAID) funding <ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.niaid.nih.gov/news/newsreleases/2005/pages/chavi.aspx |title=NIAID Funds Center for HIV/AIDS Vaccine Immunology (CHAVI) |publisher=Niaid.nih.gov |date=2005-07-14 |accessdate=2013-01-29}}</ref> of around $300 million to address key immunological roadblocks to [[HIV]] vaccine development and to design, develop and test novel [[HIV]] vaccine candidates.
==Society memberships== He is a member of [[American Academy of Arts and Sciences]], [[National Academy of Sciences]], [[American Philosophical Society]], [[European Molecular Biology Organization]], [[American Crystallographic Association]] and [[American Association for the Advancement of Science]].
==Awards==
* 1988 [[Wallace P. Rowe]] Award, [[National Institute of Allergy and Infectious Diseases]] * 1990 [[Louisa Gross Horwitz Prize]] (with Don Wiley and Michael Rossmann), [[Columbia University]] * 1995 [[George Ledlie Prize]], [[Harvard University]] * 1997 [[ICN International Prize in Virology]] * 2001 [[Paul Ehrlich and Ludwig Darmstaedter Prize]] (with Michael Rossmann) * 2005 [[Bristol-Myers Squibb Award]] for Distinguished Achievement in Infectious Diseases Research * 2006 [[Gregori Aminoff Prize]] in [[Crystallography]] * 2014 Elected as a Foreign Member of the [[Royal Society]] of London.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://royalsociety.org/people/fellowship/2014/stephen-harrison/ |title=Professor Stephen Harrison ForMemRS}}</ref>
